<div id="review_4083707624" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4083707624" />
    <a title="Erin Clemence" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16907451-erin-clemence"><img alt="Erin Clemence" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1461798513p2/16907451.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4083707624?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erin Clemence" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erin Clemence" href="/user/show/16907451-erin-clemence">Erin Clemence</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16907451-erin-clemence?shelf=kindle">kindle</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4083707624" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13773373368400139546"><b>
  <i> Thanks to the author for providing me with an electronic copy of this novel in exchange for an honest review. </i>
</b><br/><br/><i> When the body of journalist Janet Clay is found in a pool, dead of an apparent drug overdose, Aurora Stellar, overwhelmed with guilt that she did not save the woman when she had the chance, decides to attend the woman’s memorial to pay her respects. After speaking with many of the young woman’s friends, Aurora realizes that many people suspect Janet died from something other than a</i></span>
  <span id="freeText13773373368400139546" style="display:none"><b>
  <i> Thanks to the author for providing me with an electronic copy of this novel in exchange for an honest review. </i>
</b><br /><br /><i> When the body of journalist Janet Clay is found in a pool, dead of an apparent drug overdose, Aurora Stellar, overwhelmed with guilt that she did not save the woman when she had the chance, decides to attend the woman’s memorial to pay her respects. After speaking with many of the young woman’s friends, Aurora realizes that many people suspect Janet died from something other than a drug overdose and soon, Aurora is caught up in a web of lies, deceit and mistaken identity. </i><br /><br />“If Shadows Could Tell” by author Granthana Sinha feels like it should be a sequel or part of a series, as right off the bat I felt like I was missing some deeper connections between the characters. With the exception of the main character, Aurora, and her best friend, Suz, the other characters in the novel seemed to be loosely-formed acquaintances at best. It seemed anyone Aurora spoke to became her instant friend, and she would drop everything to assist them. <br /><br />The story is told in sections as opposed to chapters, intermixed with snippets from a young girl and her sister <i> (identity unknown until the very end of the novel) </i> who had fled as refugees and found safety with an as-of-yet-unknown stranger. As each section was clearly marked, with different fonts in some instances, it was easy to identify who was narrating, which made the story easy to follow. <br /><br />The plot starts as Aurora investigates the possible murder of Janet Clay, but then several more mysteries unfold around her and she begins to investigate those, too. Her one-time-acquaintance turned love-of-her-life Nicholas starts to have his own family drama, and then the investigation focuses on an old woman and her will. There seems to be a lot going on in Aurora’s little world, and the plot requires careful attention in order to follow along. <br /><br />There is an unexpected twist at the end of the novel which is unique, but I didn’t feel it fit with the novel’s genre. <br /><br />I can definitely tell Sinha has a unique writing talent, as overall the story itself was well-written <i> (with the exception of a few grammatical and spelling errors which I haven’t included in my overall rating due to the fact that it is a manuscript copy) </i> but I would’ve loved more character development, and a more centred plot, with one mystery at its core, instead of several.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13773373368400139546" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


