    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4125172231" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4125172231" />
    <a title="Rosemary Standeven" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36933045-rosemary-standeven"><img alt="Rosemary Standeven" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609179269p2/36933045.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4125172231?book_show_action=true">Aug 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rosemary Standeven" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rosemary Standeven" href="/user/show/36933045-rosemary-standeven">Rosemary Standeven</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4125172231" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18022448833705642795">It is difficult to decide into which genre to place this book. It could be a crime novel – there are certainly crimes (murder, fraud, …) – but it is not a police procedural. The police have very little input. It is not exactly a thriller – though certainly has suspense in abundance. The ending – which I really appreciated (a totally unexpected twist) – puts it right outside what you would normally expect in either of these genres. It is more a story of friendship, of family and of loss – with so</span>
  <span id="freeText18022448833705642795" style="display:none">It is difficult to decide into which genre to place this book. It could be a crime novel – there are certainly crimes (murder, fraud, …) – but it is not a police procedural. The police have very little input. It is not exactly a thriller – though certainly has suspense in abundance. The ending – which I really appreciated (a totally unexpected twist) – puts it right outside what you would normally expect in either of these genres. It is more a story of friendship, of family and of loss – with some mystery and crime thrown in. <br />The book starts, in the third person, with a brutal murder witnessed by a friend of the victim. Then a switch of scene, to first person narration by Aurora Steller, who has just lost her job, and who is asked by her best friend, Suz, to look into the disappearance of a journalist, Janet Clay. <br />There are at least two (seemingly) separate stories (differentiated by point of view, and italics), which are only brought together right at the end. People go missing, possibly dead – some, like Nicholas, reappear. But, often there seems to be no rhyme or reason. <br />I did really enjoy the book, but spent a lot of my reading time rather confused. The ending did explain most things, but I felt I had to reread the first half, to see where I had missed any hints as to the eventual outcomes. I then discovered that I had completely forgotten the brutal murder that opened the book! Yes, it is important, but I had just become so engrossed with the other threads.<br />Aura is not always a good judge of character – sometimes seeing malice where it does not in fact exist. However, almost everyone trusts her, and believes in her ability (and willingness) to help them solve their mysteries. And she does. It helps that she no longer has a job, as her investigations soon take over her life.<br /><blockquote>
  <i> “I had willingly dived in with Candice and John to do something as grave as solving someone's death. I hadn't even stopped to consider that I barely knew them. I didn't even know if they really were Janet Clay's friends.” </i>
</blockquote><br />The main characters – Aura, Suz and Nicholas – were well drawn, and very likeable. I appreciated that Aura put neither herself, nor her friends and allies, at serious risk – something that seems to happen far too often in crime/police/thriller type novels. That is not to say that all remained safe.<br />This is a novel that requires you to pay attention – something that I discovered a bit too late. It is unusual, in the way the stories pan out – and particularly in the ending. If you like your stories to be completely realistic, this may not be for you – but I liked it a lot, and found it well worth a read.<br />I received a copy of this book at no cost from the author in exchange for an honest review. All opinions are my own and not influenced by the author.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18022448833705642795" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


