    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4080339982" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4080339982" />
    <a title="Elaine Tomasso" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49861138-elaine-tomasso"><img alt="Elaine Tomasso" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4080339982?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elaine Tomasso" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elaine Tomasso" href="/user/show/49861138-elaine-tomasso">Elaine Tomasso</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4080339982" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6416711871217806730">I would like to thank the author for a review copy of If Shadows Could Tell, a stand-alone featuring involuntary amateur sleuth Aurora “Aura” Steller, set in the small Montana town of Zircon Drops.<br/><br/>When the body of journalist Janet Clay is found drowned in the local pool, a syringe at the poolside, her death is written off as a drug overdose. Aurora, upset at not being able to help Janet or Jen as she is known, soon realises that there is more to the death and starts investigating with the help o</span>
  <span id="freeText6416711871217806730" style="display:none">I would like to thank the author for a review copy of If Shadows Could Tell, a stand-alone featuring involuntary amateur sleuth Aurora “Aura” Steller, set in the small Montana town of Zircon Drops.<br /><br />When the body of journalist Janet Clay is found drowned in the local pool, a syringe at the poolside, her death is written off as a drug overdose. Aurora, upset at not being able to help Janet or Jen as she is known, soon realises that there is more to the death and starts investigating with the help of Jen’s friends.<br /><br />I enjoyed If Shadows Could Tell as it has a twisty plot that held my attention. It is told mostly from Aura’s point of view in the first person, interspersed with the history of two sisters in the third person. There is a reason for this history, but it doesn’t come out until the denouement, so for the bulk of the novel it is a cryptic tale of mental abuse and coercion. I can see what the author is trying to do with it, build a plausible backstory for present day events, but it is overdone and distracts from the main narrative. In this case less would have been more.<br /><br />Aura’s investigation is very much in the cosy, amateur sleuth vein with a scattergun approach and facts conveniently landing in her lap, be it a fortuitous connection with a hacker or people willing to confide in her. Still, it’s interesting and, while not compulsive, it certainly engages the reader and encourages them to read on. And it’s definitely worth the journey for the final twist, which I definitely didn’t expect and don’t know what to think about. It adds a certain something, although what that something is will depend on the individual reader.<br /><br />I understand that If Shadows Could Tell is a debut full length novel. It is a credible effort with a good plot and likeable characters. The polish will come with experience as it needs a bit of a change of emphasis in parts, nothing major, just small tweaks. I’m happy to recommend it. 3.5*</span>
  <a data-text-id="6416711871217806730" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


