<div id="review_3592110983" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3592110983" />
    <a title="Troy Alderman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/122798306-troy-alderman"><img alt="Troy Alderman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602508840p2/122798306.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3592110983?book_show_action=true">Oct 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Troy Alderman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Troy Alderman" href="/user/show/122798306-troy-alderman">Troy Alderman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3592110983" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1108293457248300763">&apos;If Shadows Could Tell&apos; ― it would expose all those horribly dark secrets.<br/><br/>What an apt title!<br/><br/>And the whole book ― God! It was brilliant!<br/><br/>As someone who thorougly enjoyed short stories by Granthana Sinha, I eagerly devoured the novel as soon as it was released.<br/><br/>Summary:<br/>A journalist, Janet Clay, is found dead in a local gym pool. When the media breaks the news as a case of drug-overdose, a young web designer, Aurora Steller, feels the guilt for not being able to save her. Hoping to convey her apology</span>
  <span id="freeText1108293457248300763" style="display:none">'If Shadows Could Tell' ― it would expose all those horribly dark secrets.<br /><br />What an apt title!<br /><br />And the whole book ― God! It was brilliant!<br /><br />As someone who thorougly enjoyed short stories by Granthana Sinha, I eagerly devoured the novel as soon as it was released.<br /><br />Summary:<br />A journalist, Janet Clay, is found dead in a local gym pool. When the media breaks the news as a case of drug-overdose, a young web designer, Aurora Steller, feels the guilt for not being able to save her. Hoping to convey her apology in front the dead woman's grave, she visits her memorial service and ends up suspecting there might be more to the story than what meets the eye.<br /><br /><br />Be prepared for an irresistible page-turner.<br />This is one twisted tale of deceit, where everyone is hiding secrets. Even those closest to Aurora can't be trusted for who they seem. ***I'll stop right there. Or I might give out a major spoiler!***🤐<br /><br />Also, at the end of each chapter there's a tiny subchapter that makes it all the more intense. I enjoyed it a lot!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1108293457248300763" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


